rComments: Definitely one of the best professors I've had at UofT. She's intense, her class is hard, but I feel like my understanding of Neuroscience has increased drastically. Her course is a must if you love neuroscience.

Best professor I've had so far at UofT. Her lectures are engaging and she makes a very dense course easy to understand and keep up with. That said, you need to put in the work to get a good grade. Pay attention in class and take good notes (no recording allowed). Slightly unrelated but she responds to emails very fast, which is nice.

Possibly the most interesting course I've ever taken at UofT. Although the content is dense and challenging, the lectures are delivered extremely well and it's definitely possible to do well in the course if you attend class. Overall, Dr. Morshead is an incredible professor.
So much information, better study EVERYDAY!!! or you will not do well.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Prof. Morshead is a gifted lecturer. The material is dense (HMB320), and her expectations are high (know what EVERYTHING is, as well as what it is not), but her lectures were a joy. The structure of the course is logical, she speaks clearly, lecture slides are available and so organized that I've had them bound.

Neuroanatomy is perhaps one of the most difficult courses at UofT undergradutate... and as a testament to the professor, the class average is A-. She is clear and concise. Anyone paying attention will never have to ask her a single question. The best undergrad prof at UofT -> dont shy away from her courses. Too bad she only teaches HMB320...
